e our knowledge, and motivate our actions. Contributors explore how film represents and shapes human emotion in relation to different environments and what role time, place, and genre play in these affective processes. Individual essays resituate well-researched environmental films such as An Inconvenient Truth and March of the Penguins by paying close attention to their emotionalizing strategies, and bring to our attention the affective qualities of films that have so far received little attention from ecocritics, such as Stan Brakhage’s Dog Star Man. The collection opens a new discursive space at the disciplinary intersection of film studies, affect studies, and a growing body of ecocritical scholarship. It will be of interest not only to scholars and students working in the field of ecocriticism and the environmental humanities, but for everyone with an interest in our emotional responses to film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcocriticism. 0aHuman ecology in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxPsychological aspects. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspects. 4aEnvironmental Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBrereton, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCubitt, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeumann, Joseph K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvakhiv, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonani, Salma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Robin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeymour, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular